<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-02-15T19:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-02-15T19:00:00-05:00" n="1195" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1195">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 EW/2–1545: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to the Ambassador in Venezuela</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Corrigan</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-02-15T20:00:00-04:00">February
                                    15, 1945—8 p.m.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>122. It is not clear from your recent telegrams what action Venezuela
                            contemplates with respect to entering into a state of war or
                            belligerency. However, the Foreign Office should understand that before
                            Escalante can sign the United Nations Declaration we must have a
                            Venezuelan communication to the effect that Venezuela is “at war.”</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>